            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "The rhythmic sway of the 38 Geary bus is the predictable start and end to David Sharma\u2019s day. At 37, his life is a testament to quiet dedication. As a Lead Sales Specialist for a high-end audio store near Union Square, David is a master of his domain, a world of turntables, amplifiers, and precisely engineered speakers. He can discern a customer\u2019s needs with a few gentle questions, a skill honed over nearly two decades in retail.\n\nThe son of first-generation Indian immigrants, David\u2019s story began not in a classroom, but behind the counter of his family\u2019s Daly City convenience store. While his friends were planning for college, David was helping his parents manage inventory and long hours. Higher education felt like a luxury the family couldn't afford, and David, the eldest, felt the unspoken duty to contribute. He graduated high school and went straight to work, taking a stockroom job at a big-box electronics store.\n\nThe key turning point came when a manager recognized David\u2019s innate ability to connect with people. He moved David to the sales floor, where he quickly outshone his peers. He didn't just sell; he listened, translating vague desires into tangible solutions. This success became his career path. He embraced it, working his way up through skill and reliability, not a degree.\n\nToday, David lives a comfortable but measured life in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond. His $88,000 income stretches just far enough. His social life is a small, tight-knit circle of friends, centered around weekly trivia at a neighborhood pub and sharing dim sum on Clement Street. He is deeply connected to his neighborhood's fog-laced streets and the comforting proximity of Golden Gate Park.\n\nHis dream is not one of corporate ascent but of ownership. He spends his evenings researching and saving, aspiring to one day open his own small, curated shop for vintage audio repair and sales. It would be a place that combines his deep expertise with the entrepreneurial spirit he inherited\u2014a true San Francisco story, built not on venture capital, but on passion and hard-won experience."
