            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 16, the convenience store fluorescent humming late into the night. His father, smelling of cardamom tea and exhaustion, guided his hand over the worn keys of the cash register. \"It must always balance, beta,\" he'd said. David felt a pang of resentment for his trapped youth, but it was overwhelmed by a fierce, protective love. It wasn't about numbers; it was about holding his family together. That night, duty became an instinct, a foundational part of his character.\n\n2.\nHe was 20, still in a stockroom uniform at the big-box store. An older woman looked utterly lost in the chaotic home theater aisle. His manager, a man named Frank, watched as David left his cart to help her. He didn't sell her the most expensive thing; he simply listened. Frank pulled him aside later. \"You belong on the floor,\" he said. It wasn't a promotion; it was a revelation. It was the first time someone saw his quiet competence not as a hindrance, but as a gift.\n\n3.\nA few years ago, a man brought in his late father\u2019s dusty turntable. David spent a week carefully restoring it. When they finally placed a worn jazz record on the platter, the first warm crackle filled the silent demo room. The customer\u2019s eyes welled up. In that shared hush, David understood his job wasn\u2019t just sales. He was a conservator of sound, a guardian of the intangible emotions encoded in vinyl grooves. The work became sacred.\n\n4.\nLast winter, walking home from trivia at The Plough and Stars, the fog was so thick it muffled their laughter. His friend Sarah was recounting a terrible answer they\u2019d given, and for a moment, the world shrank to their small group, the hazy streetlights, and the distant moan of a foghorn. He felt a profound sense of rightness\u2014a quiet, un-Instagrammable happiness. This, he realized, was his wealth. This was home.\n\n5.\nAbout a year ago, on the 38 Geary home, he saw it: a \"For Lease\" sign on a small, dusty storefront on Balboa. He pulled the stop cord almost by reflex and stood on the sidewalk, peering through the grimy glass. In his mind, he could instantly see shelves of vintage receivers and a small repair bench in the back. The abstract dream suddenly had a physical address. It became real, achievable, and terrifyingly urgent. His quiet savings now had a purpose."
